<div id=3D"hs_cos_wrapper_widget_1712847941833" class=3D"hs_cos_wrapper hs_=
cos_wrapper_widget hs_cos_wrapper_type_module" style=3D"" data-hs-cos-gener=
al-type=3D"widget" data-hs-cos-type=3D"module">









<div class=3D"widget_1712847941833 full-width position-relative">
   =20

<div class=3D"spacer spacer-top d-block w-100"></div>

    <div class=3D"page-center">
       =20

        <div class=3D"row align-items- justify-content-center">
            <div class=3D"full-width__content col-md-7 col-lg-8">
                <div>
                   =20
   =20

       =20

        <div class=3D"text-content">
            <h2 style=3D"font-size: 22px;"><strong>How can I calculate my w=
orking hours?</strong></h2>
<p><span data-contrast=3D"none" xml:lang=3D"EN-GB" lang=3D"EN-GB">You can c=
alculate the working hours of any week by using Breathe's working hours cal=
culator above. Just type in each working shift or use the dropdown box prov=
ided.</span></p>
<p data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []">By entering your start and end times, along wit=
h any break time in minutes, you can easily compute your total work hours f=
or the week. This tool is particularly useful for managing both full-time a=
nd part-time employees, helping you keep track of total hours worked and en=
suring compliance with working time regulations.</p>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 22px;"><strong><span data-contrast=3D"none" xml:lan=
g=3D"EN-GB" lang=3D"EN-GB">What are my maximum working hours?</span></stron=
g></h2>
<p>Maximum working hours are capped at 48 hours a week, on average, under t=
he <a href=3D"https://www.gov.uk/maximum-weekly-working-hours">working time=
 directive</a>. (This applies to adults over 18.)&nbsp;</p>
<p>If you <a href=3D"https://www.gov.uk/maximum-weekly-working-hours/weekly=
-maximum-working-hours-and-opting-out">opt out</a> of this law, you can cho=
ose to work more hours than this.</p>
<p data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []">While the legal cap is 48 hours, typical workin=
g weeks are much shorter. According to the <a target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noop=
ener noreferrer" href=3D"https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/p=
eopleinwork/earningsandworkinghours/timeseries/ybuy/lms">Office for Nationa=
l Statistics</a>, the average full-time UK employee works 36.5 hours per we=
ek (2025).</p>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 22px;"><strong>Calculating working time hours for p=
art-time employees</strong></h2>
<p>There isn=E2=80=99t an official number of weekly hours that makes someon=
e a <a href=3D"https://www.gov.uk/part-time-worker-rights#:~:text=3DThere%2=
0is%20no%20specific%20number,hours%20or%20more%20a%20week.">part-time worke=
r</a>, but a full-time worker will normally work around 35 hours per week.&=
nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 22px;"><strong>Calculating rest breaks</strong></h2=
>
<p>Legally, workers are entitled to <a href=3D"https://www.gov.uk/rest-brea=
ks-work">one uninterrupted 20-minute rest break</a> if they work more than =
6 hours per day (regardless of if they work full or part-time).&nbsp;&nbsp;=
</p>
<p>This doesn=E2=80=99t have to be paid =E2=80=93 it depends on their emplo=
yment contract whether it is or not.</p>
<h2 style=3D"font-size: 22px;" data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>How to conv=
ert hh:mm digital time to decimal hours?</strong></h2>
<p>To convert hh:mm digital time to decimal hours, you'll need to divide th=
e minutes by 60 since there are 60 minutes in an hour. For example, if you =
have a time of 7:30, this translates to 7 hours and 30 minutes. To find the=
 decimal equivalent, divide 30 by 60, which gives you 0.5. Therefore, 7:30 =
in decimal hours is 7.5.</p>
<p>This conversion is particularly useful when using a work hours calculato=
r to ensure accurate calculations of total hours worked, especially when ma=
naging payroll or tracking employee hours in a work week time sheet.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2 data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []">Examples of working hours</h2>
<div data-hs-responsive-table=3D"true" style=3D"overflow-x: auto; max-width=
: 100%; width: 99.884%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">
<table style=3D"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; table-layout: fixed=
; border: 1px solid #99acc2;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style=3D"width: 32.8289%; padding-top: 4px; padding-right: 4px; padding=
-bottom: 4px; color: #ffffff !important;">Start Time</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">End Time</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">Total Hours (Excluding breaks)=
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"width: 32.8289%; padding: 4px;">
<p>8:30 AM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>1:00 PM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>4.5</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"width: 32.8289%; padding: 4px;">
<p>9:00 AM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>5:00 PM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>8.0</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"width: 32.8289%; padding: 4px;">
<p>3:00 PM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>11:00 PM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>8.0</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"width: 32.8289%; padding: 4px;">
<p>7:00 AM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>3:30 PM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>8.5</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"width: 32.8289%; padding: 4px;">
<p>8:00 AM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>12:00 PM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>4.0</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"width: 32.8289%; padding: 4px;">
<p>9:00 AM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>5:30 PM</p>
</td>
<td style=3D"width: 33.5274%; padding: 4px;">
<p>8.5</p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p data-pm-slice=3D"1 3 []">The table above shows how different shift patte=
rns add up. If you=E2=80=99d like to check the maths yourself, here=E2=80=
=99s how it works.</p>
<h4>How to check your hours manually</h4>
<p>You can use the working hours calculator at the top of the page to add u=
p your own shifts and break times. Or, if you=E2=80=99d rather do it by han=
d, just follow this simple formula:<br><br></p>
<p><strong>Shift length =E2=88=92 Break(s) =3D Total hours worked<br><br></=
strong></p>
<p><strong>Example: 09:00 to 17:30 with a 1-hour break</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Hours: 09:00 =E2=86=92 17:00 =3D 8 hours</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Minutes: 17:00 =E2=86=92 17:30 =3D 30 minutes</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Shift length =3D 8h 30m</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Subtract break: 8h 30m =E2=88=92 60m =3D 7h 30m</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Total hours worked: 7:30</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>What is a Timesheet?</h2>
<p>A timesheet is either a document or digital tool that companies use to l=
og the number of hours each of their employees work. It records details lik=
e start and end times, breaks, and total hours worked for payroll or projec=
t tracking purposes.<br><br>They're useful because they help with accurate =
payroll processing, and can help when you have part-time employees or those=
 working irregular shifts.<br><br>Using a timesheet calculator like Breathe=
=E2=80=99s allows you to simplify this process, making it easy to log and t=
otal work hours over a day, week, or even longer periods. This ensures accu=
racy and saves time, making payroll hassle-free.</p>
        </div>

